---
/**
 * FAQ Section — 手风琴式常见问题
 */
---

<section class="faq" id="faq">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-badge">
        <i data-lucide="help-circle" class="icon-xs"></i>
        FAQ
      </span>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Sunrise & Sunset Data</h2>
      <p class="section-subtitle">Everything you need to know about SunriseTime's accuracy, coverage, and data sources.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item glass-card" id="faq-1">
        <summary>
          <span>How accurate is SunriseTime data?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="icon-sm faq-icon"></i>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>SunriseTime uses the NOAA Solar Calculator algorithm, the same standard used by the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Our sunrise and sunset predictions are accurate to within 1 minute for any location worldwide, accounting for latitude, longitude, altitude, and atmospheric refraction.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item glass-card" id="faq-2">
        <summary>
          <span>How many cities does SunriseTime cover?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="icon-sm faq-icon"></i>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>SunriseTime covers over 5,000 cities globally, sourced from the GeoNames geographical database. This includes all major metropolitan areas, popular photography destinations, and cities with over 50,000 population. We're continuously expanding coverage based on user demand.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item glass-card" id="faq-3">
        <summary>
          <span>What is golden hour and why does it matter?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="icon-sm faq-icon"></i>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Golden hour is the period shortly after sunrise and before sunset when the sun is low on the horizon, creating warm, soft, directional light. It's considered the best time for photography, filmmaking, and outdoor activities. SunriseTime calculates the exact golden hour window for your location, so you never miss that perfect light.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item glass-card" id="faq-4">
        <summary>
          <span>How are prayer times calculated?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="icon-sm faq-icon"></i>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Prayer times are calculated using the PrayTimes algorithm, which supports multiple juristic methods including University of Islamic Sciences (Karachi), Islamic Society of North America (ISNA), Muslim World League, and Umm al-Qura. You can select your preferred calculation method for the most accurate results.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item glass-card" id="faq-5">
        <summary>
          <span>Does SunriseTime work well on mobile?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="icon-sm faq-icon"></i>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Yes. SunriseTime is designed to answer the main question quickly on smaller screens: what time is sunrise, what time is sunset, and what comes next. Search, city pages, and the key timing cards are all optimized to stay legible and tappable on mobile devices.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item glass-card" id="faq-6">
        <summary>
          <span>Is SunriseTime free to use?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="icon-sm faq-icon"></i>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Absolutely! SunriseTime is 100% free to use — no account required, no hidden fees. All features including sunrise/sunset times, golden hour tracking, moon phase data, prayer time calculations, and the API are completely free for everyone. We sustain the platform through unobtrusive advertising.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
